-- Spain Falls Short of Maximum Goal Set for Bills Auction as Yields Increase
-- B y   P a u l   T o b i n
-- 2010-11-16T10:01:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-16/spain-sells-4-97-billion-eurs-of-bills-at-auction-below-maximum-target.html
Spain sold 5 billion euros ($6.8
billion) of Treasury bills, less than the maximum target of 5.5
billion euros set for its regular monthly auction, the Bank of
Spain said.  The Treasury sold 3.73 billion euros of 12-month bills at
an average yield of 2.363 percent, compared with 1.842 percent
when the securities were last sold on Oct. 19. It also sold 1.24
billion euros of 18-month bills at 2.664 percent compared with
2.009 percent last month. Demand for the 12-month paper was 1.9
times the amount sold, compared with 2.06 times in October, and
3.66 times for the longer-dated bills, up from 2.03 last month.  Spain is facing higher borrowing costs as the capital needs
of Irelandâ€™s banking industry threaten to deepen the sovereign
debt crisis that was triggered by Greece. Euro-region finance
ministers meet today in Brussels while European Central Bank
officials urge Ireland to tap the 750 billion-euro fund created
in May to prevent the crisis from spreading.  The extra yield investors demand to hold Spanish 10-year
benchmark  bonds  instead of German equivalents rose 5 basis
points today to 199 basis points.  To contact the reporter on this story:
